!NC!!Semantic<br>field!!Noun<br>-C, -V!!Subj.!!Obj!!''-a''!!Adjective<br>-C, -i, -e<ref group="*">Most Swahili adjectives begin with either a consonant or the vowels ''i-'' or ''e-,'' which are listed separately above. The few adjectives which begin with other vowels do not agree with all noun classes, since some are restricted to humans. NC 1 ''m(w)-'' is ''mw-'' before ''a'' and ''o,'' and reduces to ''m-'' before ''u''; ''wa-'' does not change; and ''ki-, vi-, mi-'' become ''ch-, vy-, my-'' before ''o'' but not before ''u'': ''mwanana, waanana'' "gentle", ''mwororo, waororo, myororo, chororo, vyororo'' "mild, yielding", ''mume, waume, kiume, viume'' "male".</ref>
